Without loss of generality, we may assume that f has an inverse 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen g,\epsilon ,\eta ,\chi \right \rparen \mathclose {}
. By , it suffices to argue that the type of inverses to f is a retract of a proposition; the type of inverses to f is in fact equivalent to the type of sections equipped with a coherent remainder:

By , it suffices to show that the type of sections to f is a proposition and that for every such section, the coherent remainder thereof is a proposition. The latter is , and the former follows from  by means of the retraction 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen g,\eta \right \rparen \mathclose {}
.

